help  perlbug 1.35 running under perl v5.8.8.  please enter your report here this perl is configured with 64bit integers  64bit floats 152 bits  significand.  perl lwe  package t0 sub mynum subject: re: [opensuse] opensuse 11
emailtext: benji weber wrote  on 07/02/2008 mike wrote  the notion that malware  linux was technically not feasible is  highly irrational. i think experienced senior linux users shouldnt  keep  spreading this deceptive mantra. you should know better.  why is it irrational? i disagree with that statement. unless you can   course show me  attachment that autoexecutes under linux.    malware is not entirely about root remember? john doe user accounts  with dsl pipes privacy breaches appscandoall etc. you know   list.  no its not all about root. but it is about doing something stupid.  theres no other way  describe it. first it has  be  downloaded/saved. then it has  be made executable. then it has  be  run. if all three things are done then yes you have  problem. but  its  three step process.   this is not  case. a browser running as  user can do anything   user is allowed  do. for example  exploit   browser  image  viewing library which can be exploited through malicious javascript   crafted image could potentially delete all your user files. it could  be used  launch  denial  service attack  spam from your machine  no need  root  this. if combined with  local root exploit  which are not uncommon it could potentially even get root  have  full control over  system. same applies  your mail client irc  client  other such applications.   this is why it is important  both keep  software up  date   still not run untrusted code. if you completely ignore security by  blindly visiting pages with possible malware   running all email  attachments etc even  opensuse/gnu/linux you are vulnerable.   there are technologies which can help like apparmor/selinux etc   these are not yet user friendly enough  desktop users  use.   if you have  ssh server listening   internet  you watch your  logs i would be surprised if you have not noticed brute force attacks.  precautions such as strong passwords  fail2ban are important even   home machines if you run sshd.   gnu/linux systems are no less exploitable than windows. in some  respects they are more exploitable due   more powerful tools they  have installed. windows tends  be fairly locked down by default now.   the only reason you have  false sense  security now is that you are  not  significant enough target  malware authors. when that changes  if too many people have  same attitude then there will be   problem. worstcase scenario is loss  personal data / runaway process which consumes resources memory  disk space if not constrained by ulimit  quota until theres  system crash. what you wont have  do is reinstall  whole system. you see... whole unix security model presumed that  user might either unintentionally  intentionally write / execute  runaway process which could be destructive. writepermissions  lack  them prevent  process from doing damage  anything other than  users own personal files.

emailtext: sloan wrote  wolfgang woehl wrote  aaron kulkis   sloan wrote   philippe landau wrote   i almost never click   tinyurl  as i dont know what it hides.   im  linux user i click  anything i feel like without fear   viruses  spyware    same here.   security by insignificance? id consider getting rid  that habit  whenever it will be judged by interested parties that linux desktops  now ranged   significant amounts. or your specific box gets   be judged significant.    it always seems  man   street assumes that microsoft suffers  from such chronic security woes only because   overwhelming  popularity  ms windows  doesnt consider that script kiddies are  just taking  low hanging fruit  easy target. in actuality ms windows  other products suffer chronic security problems because ms deliberately places backdoors  their products. ever notice how it sometimes takes months between when  windows security problem is first reported  when  problem is finally admitted right as they are releasing  patch? thats because sometimes it takes that long  not only close  backdoor which  crackers have discovered   also create a new backdoor so that they can continue monitoring  spying upon  customer base.   ive been using unix too long  be scared by  viruses are coming  be afraid crowd. sure its possible  exploit cartain scenarios   linux  other unixlike systems  by  nature   design its  not as straightforward  simple as infecting  peecee operating system.  yep. see above. unix  linux are written with  idea that multiple users will be logged  at  same time that all  them are creative  not infallible programmers   system must be resiliant enough  prevent any users faulty code from crashing  destroying  whole system. this is  basis   nix security model. windows is written with  idea that everybody is perfect  nothing bad  unexpected happens  ever. this is why windows doesnt really have  security model.  prudence  reasonable security measures are appropriate  linux  users  blind paranoia is not.   joe

subject: ceas 2007 live spam challenge
emailtext: ceas 2007 live spam challenge thursday august 2nd  friday august 3rd 2007 microsoft research silicon valley mountain view california call for participation the conference  email  antispam ceas invites participation   ceas live spam challenge. participants will compete  filtering  live 24hour email stream delivered using standard protocols smtp imap4 pop3. all types  antispam technology are welcome including servers appliances proxies  personal filters. participants will be allowed  use any network resource including realtime blacklists realtime whitelists reversedns queries  privately owned  updated databases. simulated userfeedback will be provided  train learningbased filters. filters will be evaluated based   weighted combination   percentage  spam blocked  its false positive percentage. the challenge will be held  conjunction with  fourth annual conference  email  antispam ceas. conference registration  attendance is not required  participation. please see http//www.ceas.cc/challenge  competition details  instructions  joining  competition email list. key dates  toolkit available may 1st 2007.  test stream beginning may 1st 2007.  competition august 2nd  august 3rd 2007 contact  the organizers can be reached at informationceas.cc. organizers  richard segal ibm research http//www.research.ibm.com/people/r/rsegal  gordon cormack university  waterloo http//plg.uwaterloo.ca/gvcormac  ceasannounce mailing list hwgfqazypeenlists.stanford.edu https//mailman.stanford.edu/mailman/listinfo/ceasannounce

again. so let  me know if any   skipped threads should be brought .  corrections  comments welcome as always.     announcements       summaries       about ssl tests     an open bug about missing ssl tests 451607 was brought up  close  keep  open. jeanpaul calderone mentioned  improved testing method by spawning   openssl sserver  testing purposes. this sparked some talk about   terminating  subprocesses   crossplatform manner see crossplatform  subprocess termination.   contributing thread    about ssl tests       crossplatform subprocess termination     because os.kill only works  nix  os x platforms leaving windows  platforms uncovered. although subprocess.terminateprocess exists  windows  platforms it requires  use  handles  additional overhead  use.  support was overall given  adding  unixonly signal method   cross  platform terminate method  popen instances. nothing was said  actually  incorporating these changes into  subprocess module although code was  given.   contributing thread    this was mixed  with  about ssl tests thread.     extended buffer protocol     updates   buffer protocol are discussed along with  proposal prepep  documenting  updates  python 3000  brought  pythondev due so   plans  backporting  2.6 afterwards.   note i couldnt summarize this well enough  cover much  it do any real  degree  it is currently  py3k issue so maybe that is ok. if no one wants   add   summary it will stay short.   contributing threads    extended buffer pep     pep 3118 extended buffer protocol new version     extended buffer protocol  simple use examples       function  counting items   sequence     a patch was submitted by steven bethard http//bugs.python.org/1696199  implemented  discussed collections.counts function  provide  mapping  between items   iterable   number  times they appear. there were  suggested names  none overthrew  original counts   question   items not appearing being counted as 0  raising  keyerror with 0 winning  due   justmakessense factor.   contributing thread    function  counting items   sequence       context manager  generator interaction?     a problem was brought up with iterator context managers  iteration inside   withblock raising its stopiteration  being caught by  context  manager mechanics. it was also responded that  problem would not exist  without  use  overly broad try blocks  this lead   addition    formal note  pep 8 about keeping narrow try blocks.   contributing thread    context manager  generator interaction?       proposed which.py replacement     suggestion  replacing  which.py discussing mirnas  cancer. the role  mirnas  human disease including cancer is now well established. many questions remain however such as precisely how mirnas exert their effects whether they make february 8 2008 319 5864 editors choice highlights of the recent literature geology the ups  downs  stress brooks hanson the hawaiian islands have formed sequentially as  pacific ocean crust has moved over  locus  melting   mantle. as each island grows  huge weight  cooled magma  pile extending many kilometers above  ocean floor bends  ocean crust downward. two related large mw  6.0  6.7 earthquakes struck  island  hawaii  15 october 2006  have helped reveal important aspects  this process. both earthquakes occurred   mantle. one was particularly deep 39 km below  surface  implied local extension  other was shallower at  depth  about 19 km  suggested lateral compression. through finiteelement modeling mcgovern shows that  different mechanisms reflect modification   broad bending process by  different strengths   lower crust  mantle producing compression at depths shallower than about 32 km  extension below with strain focused near  depth   deeper quake. in addition compression at  depth  19 km would tend  restrict  ascent  magmas consistent with  notion that  crust is being underplated by cooled magmas at this depth.  bh geophys. res. lett. 34 l23305 2007. plant viroid are smaller  lumpier than usual   viroids move through  leaf cells into  phloem  then   distant parts. the pstvd rna adopts  rodshaped structure  all   loops were essential  fully successful optical  electronic properties. researchers discovered   1980s that photons can behave   similar way optical materials fabricated with just  right periodic structures exhibit energy  frequency regions where light passes through  other energy zones where transmission  light is blocked. just as semiconductor band gaps lead   wide range  useful technological properties photonic band gaps can do  same  optical materials. researchers have assumed that  order  produce  photonic band gaps highquality crystalline materials are required. edagawa et al. present computational results showing that amorphous diamond without lattice periodicity can also exhibit strong photonic band gaps. the results challenge  traditional view that photonic band gaps are strictly  consequence  bragg reflection  interference  which electromagnetic waves are scattered from various planes formed by  periodic atomic lattice. thus  range  photonic band gap systems could potentially be synthesized from materials such as polymers proteins  colloids that lend themselves naturally  amorphous structures.  dv phys. rev. lett. 100 13901 2008. physics profiles  charge ian s. osborne the availability  highpower subject: [ spambayes-patches-1707814 ] more resilient parsing for sb_imapfilter
emailtext: patches item 1707814 was opened at 20070425 2231 message generated  change settings changed made by davidabrahams you can respond by visiting https//sourceforge.net/tracker/?funcdetail&atid498105&aid1707814&groupid61702 please note that this message will contain  full copy   comment thread including  initial issue submission  this request not just  latest update. category none group none status open resolution none priority 5 private no submitted by david abrahams davidabrahams assigned  tony meyer anadelonbrin summary more resilient parsing  sbimapfilter initial comment on 31 january 2006 i posted this problem that came up  me trying  do training with sbimapfilter with  latest cvs loading state from /usr/home/dave/hammie.new.db database /usr/home/dave/hammie.new.db is  new database loading database /usr/home/dave/hammie.new.db... done. account www.stlport.com993 training training ham folder hambox traceback most recent call last file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 1283  ? run file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 1261  run imapfilter.train file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 1004  train numtrained  folder.trainself.classifier isspam file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 888  train  msg  self file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 799  iter yield selfkey file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 831  getitem data  self.imapserver.extractfetchdataresponsedata file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 455  extractfetchdata msgdata  self.extractfetchdatamsg file /usr/home/dave/src/spambayes/scripts/sbimapfilter.py line 428  extractfetchdata raise badimapresponseerrorfetch response response main.badimapresponseerror the command fetch response failed  give  ok response.  uid 1967 i decided last week  try  debug this  little bit myself. i know almost nothing about  workings  imap   problem appears  be that sbimapfilter isnt accounting  responses like this one   6 body 3130 returnpath mailerdaemon...about 3000 characters snipped...  uid 6  in particular that last fragment is where sbimapfilter gets upset. i dont know whether  real bug is  whatever gets passed  sbimapfilter  be used as its server attribute  whether its here  if you look carefully at  response data structure above which is passed back from  server object  sbimapfilter youll see that  parenthesization that was   original text coming back from  real imap server i.e.  computer is violated by  data structure which leads me  believe that  problem might be  whatever is parsing that response into  data structure  server object i presume... although im not sure what it is actually supposed  be doing  this case so its hard  say the following patch which given my scant knowledge is almost certainly wrong makes  problem disappear  me.  you can respond by visiting https//sourceforge.net/tracker/?funcdetail&atid498105&aid1707814&groupid61702

emailtext: http//issues.apache.org/spamassassin/showbug.cgi?id5813  additional comments from wrzzpvsidney.com 20080208 0110  reply  comment 4  using  official tld table should usually be preferred i see i didnt make explicit  comment 2 what i did   attachment 4257. that patch does what i talked about  comment 1 i.e. it fixes  table  util/registrarboundaries.pm  match  official tld table at http//data.iana.org/tld/tldsalphabydomain.txt with  exception   idn test entries  it redoes  regexp  permsgstatus.pm  be  regexplist optimized form  that table. however i should mention  discussion from  sadev list  which it was pointed out that there are some tlds that are defunct with no domains  active registrar. these are bv gb pm sj so um yt which perhaps should be rmoved from  list because they cannot point   valid url  mail address so could only cause fps.  you are receiving this mail because  you are  assignee   bug  are watching  assignee.

subject: caller() info in destroy off?
emailtext: while investigating some issues with regards  object destruction i came upon this little oddity. take this program  foo  sub foodestroy  undef filename line  caller print called from filename line linen  my foo  bless  foo undef foo  destruction not reported at this line my bar  line at which destruction  object is reported  if you run this you get called from foo line 9 it seems that  caller info is pointing   next executable line line 9 rather than where  actual destruction is taking place line 7. well at least where  destruction is taking place from  naive users point  view.  i assume this is basically  way it is right? seems  be like this  every version  perl i could get my hands . liz

subject: re: caller() info in destroy off?
emailtext: on 03/10/2007 elizabeth mattijsen wrote  while investigating some issues with regards  object destruction i  came upon this little oddity. take this program    foo   sub foodestroy   undef filename line  caller  print called from filename line linen     my foo  bless  foo  undef foo  destruction not reported at this line   my bar  line at which destruction  object is reported well  destruction technically happens after  undef instruction has finished. so  current cop points at  next statement. which might be far away...  might even not have  line number associated  it. that happens if  undef call is done at  end   end block. i understand that might be not practical  thats  first time i hear about this problem  i dont have really  idea about  possible  efficient solution.

subject: [python-dev] april 1-15 2007 summaries final draft
emailtext: if no one has any further comments over  weekend  monday ill post it as  final summary that evening/night.  announcements   summaries   about ssl tests  an open bug about missing ssl tests 451607 was brought up  close  keep open. jeanpaul calderone mentioned  improved testing method by spawning  openssl sserver  testing purposes. this sparked some talk about  terminating  subprocesses   crossplatform manner see crossplatform subprocess termination. contributing thread  about ssl tests   crossplatform subprocess termination  because os.kill only works  nix  os x platforms leaving windows platforms uncovered. although subprocess.terminateprocess exists  windows platforms it requires  use  handles  additional overhead  use. support was overall given  adding  unixonly signal method   cross platform terminate method  popen instances. nothing was said  actually incorporating these changes into  subprocess module although code was given. contributing thread  this was mixed  with  about ssl tests thread.  extended buffer protocol  updates   buffer protocol are discussed along with  proposal prepep documenting  updates  python 3000  brought  pythondev due so  plans  backporting  2.6 afterwards. note i couldnt summarize this well enough  cover much  it do any real degree  it is currently  py3k issue so maybe that is ok. if no one wants  add   summary it will stay short. contributing threads  extended buffer pep   pep 3118 extended buffer protocol new version   extended buffer protocol  simple use examples   function  counting items   sequence  a patch was submitted by steven bethard http//bugs.python.org/1696199 implemented  discussed collections.counts function  provide  mapping between items   iterable   number  times they appear. there were suggested names  none overthrew  original counts   question  items not appearing being counted as 0  raising  keyerror with 0 winning due   justmakessense factor. contributing thread  function  counting items   sequence   context manager  generator interaction?  a problem was brought up with iterator context managers  iteration inside  withblock raising its stopiteration  being caught by  context manager mechanics. it was also responded that  problem would not exist without  use  overly broad try blocks  this lead   addition   formal note  pep 8 about keeping narrow try blocks. contributing thread  context manager  generator interaction?   proposed which.py replacement  suggestion  replacing  which.py script   tools directory migrated  its proposal  inclusion into  standard subject: [bug 5813] [review] several tlds are not parsed by uri text scanner in permsgstatus.pm
emailtext: http//issues.apache.org/spamassassin/showbug.cgi?id5813  additional comments from wrzzpvsidney.com 20080208 0258  here is  summary  comments from sadev that should be here   record  michael parker said would anyone object  removing .so from this list? the .so tld is basically dead  weve found that lots  bogus domains like lib.so are being caught by this. also sometimes youll have spammers who are putting  gibberish  funny punctuation  youll get sentences like blah blah.so this is. it also occurs with  couple  other domains  .so is by far  worst. for more info   .so domain you can read about it here http//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.so28domainname29  to which i replied after reading  wikipedia entries   tlds that they list as unused i would be  favor  removing all  them bv gb pm sj so um yt if spammers cant use them as domains then all including them could do would be  generate false positives. the three listed as phaseout su tp yu   other hand i would keep because it appears from  wikipedia articles that they are  active use either during  transition period  because their phaseout is being resisted. if we can reach consensus  this ill make  changes   code i committed.  and then justin mason said im happy enough with that. btw this discussion should be   bug...  and here we are  you are receiving this mail because  you are  assignee   bug  are watching  assignee.

subject: [uai] ecir05: call for papers
emailtext: first announcement  call  papers bcsirsg ecir05 27th european conference  information retrieval 2123 march 2005 santiago de compostela spain http//wwwgsi.dec.usc.es/ecir05/ kbth04usc.es sponsored by european research consortium  informatics & mathematics ercim microsoft research sharp laboratories  europe call  papers the annual european conference  information retrieval is  main european forum   presentation  new research results   field  information retrieval. we encourage  submission  highquality research papers reporting new unpublished  innovative research results within information retrieval. the conference intends  cover all aspects  accessing digital information without explicitly specified semantics. papers whose sole  main author is  msc phd  postdoctoral student are especially welcome. topics  interest include  are not limited  ir models techniques  algorithms searching browsing metasearching data fusion filtering  indexing text  content classification mining extraction  summarisation topic detection  tracking personalised collaborative recommender useradaptive ir improvements  existing  new ir models compression performance optimisation users society  ir user modelling user studies user interaction  ir systems novel user interfaces  ir systems visualisation  presentation  queries search results  content information management crosslanguage  multilanguage ir ir applications web ir mobile  ubiquitous ir digital libraries ir system architectures distributed parallel mobile multimodal open interoperable  flexible content representation  processing ir  structured content e.g. xml based unstructured content meta information  structures test  evaluation methods  ir systems test collections  bench marking useroriented  usercentred test  evaluation multimedia  crossmedia ir speech  ir image  video ir digital music radio  tv all papers will be refereed through blind peer review. accepted papers will appear   proceedings published by springerverlag   lecture notes  computer science series which will be distributed  all delegates at  conference. poster submissions addressing any   areas identified   conference topics are also invited. authors are encouraged  demonstrate work  progress  latebreaking research results. poster abstracts 3 pages will be included   proceedings. an award will be presented   author   best student paper. submission details  manuscripts should be submitted electronically  ps  pdf format  close accord with  springer lecture notes  computer science guidelines http//www.springeronline.com/sgw/cda/frontpage/0107355164272376000.html. authors are encouraged  use latex2e  preparing  manuscript using  llncs template available from  springer website. papers prepared under different text processing systems are also acceptable provided that  springer lncs instructions are strictly observed. papers cannot exceed 15 pages  length including references. poster abstracts which should follow  same formatting instructions cannot exceed 3 pages including references. one author per paper is required  register  attend  conference  present  paper if accepted  publication. important dates  paper submission 1 november 2004 poster submission 8 november 2004 notification  all submissions 9 december 2004 final copy due 22 december 2004 contacts  if you have any queries  problems concerning submitting  paper please contact any   conference chairs dr. david e. losada grupo de sistemas inteligentes dept. electrnica y computacin universidad de santiago de compostela campus sur s/n 15782 santiago de compostela spain tel 34 981563100 x13572 fax 34 981528012 email zbmzboausc.es dr. juan m. fernndez luna grupo de tratamiento de incertidumbre en inteligencia artificial departamento de ciencias de la computacin e inteligencia artificial universidad de granada escuela tcnica superior de ingenier informtica c/ periodista daniel saucedo aranda s/n. 18071 granada spain tel 34 958 240465 fax 34 958 243317 email drymrlkdecsai.ugr.es

subject: [python-dev] os.rename on windows
emailtext: hi i have submitted  patch http//www.python.org/sf/1704547 that allows os.rename  replace  destination file if it exists  windows. as part  discussion   tracker martin suggested that pythondev should discuss  change. currently os.rename  windows uses  api movefile which fails if  destination file exists. the patch replaces this api with movefileex  uses  flag movefilereplaceexisting which causes  destination file  be replaced if it exists. however this change is subtle  if there is any existing code that depends  current os.rename behaviour  windows their code is silently broken with any destination file being overwritten. but  functionality  replacing is important  i would like  know  best  way  supporting it. if it is deemed that this change is not good  go  asis how about having  optional parameter  os.rename say winreplace that can be used by callers  explicitly request replacing? i must also point out that  patch uses another flag movefilecopyallowed effectively allowing renamed files  be  separate file systems. the renaming  this case is not atomic  i used this flag only  support current functionality. it is not  bad idea  disallow such renames which brings it  line with  behaviour  many unix flavors. this also has  potential  break code  not silently. lastly i found  old discussion about  same topic by this list. http//mail.python.org/pipermail/pythondev/2001may/014957.html even though guido indicated that he doesnt support api change  this thread i am posting again as i did not see any one mention movefileex  that thread. thanks raghu.  pythondev mailing list zvlllneumpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pythondev unsubscribe http//mail.python.org/mailman/options/pythondev/pythondev40tangomu.com

subject: sasl questions
emailtext: hi i have  couple  questions regarding sasl. in main.cf i have  smtpdsasllocaldomain smtpdsaslpathsmtpd brokensaslauthclientsyes smtpdrecipientrestrictionspermitmynetworkspermitsaslauthenticatedrejectunauthdestination smtpdsenderrestrictionschecksenderaccess hash/etc/postfix/blocksendershash/etc/postfix/mydomains smtpdsenderloginmapsldap/etc/postfix/localrecipients.cf smtpdsenderrestrictionsrejectauthenticatedsenderloginmismatch smtpdrestrictionclassesverifylogin verifyloginrejectsenderloginmismatch   mydomains mydomain1 verifylogin mydomain2 verifylogin  using this configuration user1mydomain1 cannot pretend he is  different user. for example he cannot send  email saying he is user2mydomain2. question1 how can i exclude  user from this rule based  his ip?  main.cf ive added mynetworks127.0.0.1 hisipaddress  it does not work. question2 the rule above works fine  all users when they use  webmail client  any other client. the only problem is with users who use squirrelmail. they still can send emails with  fake from address postfix cannot stop them. any ideas? thanks  advance alex

subject: re: [dkim-milter-discuss] postfix + dkim-filter + email lists - milter  troubles (cant read smfic_header
emailtext: daniel black skrev  08022008 1111  had some trouble deploying dkimmilter2.4.4  postfix2.4.6 debian etch backports  tried etch 2.3.8  had  same troubles  mailman2.1.97.   dkimmilter is deployed  signing  verifing mode with its primary intent  sign emails  lists.cacert.org mailing lists.   feb 7 092709 lists postfix/master22912 daemon started  version 2.4.6 configuration /etc/postfix  i deployed it as  typical  sole milter  smtpdmilters  unixexternmilter/dkimfilter.sock  nonsmtpdmilters  smtpdmilters   testing   tiny email list   email came through signed by dkim.   feb 7 102829   email when through   larger email list poptemkkrrvqlists.cacert.org without any error   after  significant number  hours without  peep out  dkimfilter i start  get.   feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 f13c6108238 messageid95690946646473.5e95gt09s6hlin.cacert.org  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 warning milter unixexternmilter/dkimfilter.sock cant read smficheader reply packet header connection reset by peer  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 f13c6108238 milterreject endofmessage from lists.cacert.org172.16.2.17 4.7.1 service unavailable  try again later from  protoesmtp helo  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/smtpd15071 disconnect from lists.cacert.org172.16.2.17  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/smtpd15071 connect from lists.cacert.org172.16.2.17  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/smtpd15071 05de1108238 clientlists.cacert.org172.16.2.17  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 05de1108238 messageid95690946646473.5e95gt09s6hlin.cacert.org  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 warning milter unixexternmilter/dkimfilter.sock cant read smficheader reply packet header connection reset by peer  feb 7 144005 lists postfix/cleanup15075 05de1108238 milterreject endofmessage from lists.cacert.org172.16.2.17 4.7.1 service unavailable  try again later from  protoesmtp helo   these occured  these same  email recipients every 15 minutes from until feb 7 210015 when i woke up   haze. noticed it was failing  turned it off.  the dkimmilter still seems  be running happliy  its unix socket.   this is also noted   http//sourceforge.net/mailarchive/message.php?msgid476123d1.500060240hetnet.nl   second error. i still cant get  total grasp  whats happing though.   any tips  how  isolate this error would be really welcome as i really dont want  be trialing   live system too much. i notice you cite my post i stick  what i wrote postfix 2.5  my case has no trouble with dkimmilter 2.4.3  mailings  over 1000 ldap posixgroup based recipients at  time. but unix sockets have given problems   past inet none. and all my dkimmilter based stuff is called out  master.cg not main.cf. dkimmilter is called by my last smtpd listener before  message goes  cleanup. best tonni  tony earnshaw email tonni at hetnet dot nl

subject: re: [r] greek characters in plots
emailtext: on tue 5 aug 2008 michael watson iahc wrote  ok i am definitely struggling here.   the text i am trying  plot isnt  mathematical expression its   a stbacat ok so you want  greek character  not  greek symbol. as i said they are different different fonts different shapes aka glyphs.  this is biological notation   particular mutation. the a part is   tag identifying  graph   stbacat bit is  gene that is  mutated. both  tag  gene are set as variables   loop  only   delta remains  same.   as  text i am trying  plot isnt  mathematical expression i seem   be having trouble getting substitute  expression  do what i  want. as plotmath states a mathematical expression must obey   normal rules  syntax  any r expression i fear i may be barking up   wrong tree   thank you all  your help so far  can someone please help me once  more  tell me how i can get  capital delta symbol so i can use it   nonmathematical text  strings  plotting?   a b  stbacat paste u0394 b number from http//www.alanwood.net/unicode/greek.html . this should work   utf8 locale  also  windows   windows device    rgui console.   thanks once again   mick   original message  from prof brian ripley mailtoripleystats.ox.ac.uk  sent 05 august 2008 1240  to michael watson iahc  cc henrique dallazuanna rhelprproject.org  subject re r greek characters  plots   on tue 5 aug 2008 michael watson iahc wrote   excellent i even tried delta  not delta....   ?plotmath says   alpha  omega uppercase greek symbols   how could that be made clearer?   note it carefully says greek symbols not character they are not   same thing.   now how do i go about pasting that with some text that i have  various other variables?   use substitute? e.g.   substituteexpressionfoodelta listfoo3   some people prefer bquote  that is just  wrapper  substitute   r.    original message  from henrique dallazuanna mailtowwwhsdgmail.com  sent 05 august 2008 1217  to michael watson iahc  cc rhelprproject.org  subject re r greek characters  plots   try   expressiondelta   on tue aug 5 2008 at 814 am michael watson iahc  wrote  hi   i am running  r script that creates 100s  graphs  i need  use   greek capital letter delta   mtext function.   i got as far as expressiondelta  this gives me  lowercase  version.   can anyone help? im using r 2.7  windows xp   mick   head  informatics  institute  animal health  compton  berks  rg20 7nn  01635 578411   http//www.iah.ac.uk/research/bioinformatics/bioinf.shtml   the information contained  this message may be confide...dropped14     rhelprproject.org mailing list  https//stat.ethz.ch/mailman/listinfo/rhelp  please do read  posting guide http//www.rproject.org/postingguide.html   provide commented minimal selfcontained reproducible code.        henrique dallazuanna  curitibaparanbrasil  25 25 40 s 49 16 22 o     rhelprproject.org mailing list  https//stat.ethz.ch/mailman/listinfo/rhelp  please do read  posting guide http//www.rproject.org/postingguide.html   provide commented minimal selfcontained reproducible code.      brian d. ripley ripleystats.ox.ac.uk  professor  applied statistics http//www.stats.ox.ac.uk/ripley/  university  oxford tel 44 1865 272861 self  1 south parks road 44 1865 272866 pa  oxford ox1 3tg uk fax 44 1865 272595   brian d. ripley ripleystats.ox.ac.uk professor  applied statistics http//www.stats.ox.ac.uk/ripley/ university  oxford tel 44 1865 272861 self 1 south parks road 44 1865 272866 pa oxford ox1 3tg uk fax 44 1865 272595

emailtext: daniel black skrev  08022008 1319  on fri 8 feb 2008 104135 pm tony earnshaw wrote   i notice you cite my post i stick  what i wrote postfix 2.5  my  case has no trouble with dkimmilter 2.4.3  mailings  over 1000  ldap posixgroup based recipients at  time. but unix sockets have given  problems   past inet none.   i just assumed that unix vs inet problems were chroot related however im  willing  try  inet path i was limited due  vserver firewall rules  when i dont control  host.   and all my dkimmilter based stuff is  called out  master.cg not main.cf. dkimmilter is called by my last  smtpd listener before  message goes  cleanup.   can you please provide  config you use? master.cf 10026 is  last  three smtpd listeners 10026 inet n  n  50 smtpd o contentfilter o smtpdclientrestrictions o smtpdhelorestrictions o smtpdsenderrestrictions o smtpderrorsleeptime0 o smtpdrecipientrestrictionspermitmynetworksreject o receiveoverrideoptionsnounknownrecipientchecks o smtpdmiltersinetlocalhost10004 o disablemimeoutputconversionyes o miltermacrodaemonnameoriginating o milterdefaultactionaccept default milterprotocol is 3 6 as advised  pf 2.5 does give smficheader faults. miltermacrodaemonname corresponds  mta originating  /etc/dkimfilter.conf  even though people have written that thats not necessary any more with current versions  dkimmilter. best tonni  tony earnshaw email tonni at hetnet dot nl

subject: re: [dkim-milter-discuss] postfix + dkim-filter + email lists - milter troubles (cant read smfic_header
emailtext: tony earnshaw  master.cf 10026 is  last  three smtpd listeners   10026 inet n  n  50 smtpd safety use 127.0.0.110026 wietse  o contentfilter  o smtpdclientrestrictions  o smtpdhelorestrictions  o smtpdsenderrestrictions  o smtpderrorsleeptime0  o smtpdrecipientrestrictionspermitmynetworksreject  o receiveoverrideoptionsnounknownrecipientchecks  o smtpdmiltersinetlocalhost10004  o disablemimeoutputconversionyes  o miltermacrodaemonnameoriginating  o milterdefaultactionaccept   default milterprotocol is 3 6 as advised  pf 2.5 does give  smficheader faults.   miltermacrodaemonname corresponds  mta originating   /etc/dkimfilter.conf  even though people have written that thats not  necessary any more with current versions  dkimmilter.   best   tonni     tony earnshaw  email tonni at hetnet dot nl

subject: wekalist digest vol 60 issue 12
emailtext: send wekalist mailing list submissions  iuxxdkqklist.scms.waikato.ac.nz to subscribe  unsubscribe via  world wide web visit https//list.scms.waikato.ac.nz/mailman/listinfo/wekalist  via email send  message with subject  body help  ohwwlejspbfotbplist.scms.waikato.ac.nz you can reach  person managing  list at pobypuhshvhzjlist.scms.waikato.ac.nz when replying please edit your subject line so it is more specific than re contents  wekalist digest... todays topics 1. adding  new filterjar generation cristina torres 2. gridregression.py m. fatih akay 3. re multilayerperceptron results harri m.t. saarikoski 4. re repath variable danilovich yann  from lmjznprcyynlydlfhotmail.com sun feb 24 102737 2008 message 1 date fri 8 feb 2008 103701 0000 from cristina torres subject wekalist adding  new filterjar generation to weka machine learning workbench list. messageid contenttype text/plain charsetiso88591 hello finally i solve  problem   compilation  weka  i also introduce  new filter filter.java   filters folders now i want  create  .jar document   complete weka with my new filter i generate  jar file  when i try  execute it have this error failed  lad main class manifiest atribute somebody knows how i have  generate this .jar file properly? cris express yourself instantly with msn messenger msn messenger  express yourself instantly with msn messenger download today its free http//messenger.msn.clickurl.com/go/onm00200471ave/direct/01/  next part  an html attachment was scrubbed... url https//list.scms.waikato.ac.nz/pipermail/wekalist/attachments/20080208/9baf78e4/attachment0001.html  from kylwi0776yahoo.com sun feb 24 102737 2008 message 2 date fri 8 feb 2008 032411 0800 pst from m. fatih akay subject wekalist gridregression.py to weka messageid 641465.488.qmweb52802.mail.re2.yahoo.com contenttype text/plain charsetiso88591 mark/peter is it possible  integrate gridregression.py   similar tool which is  tool under libsvm  finding  optimized parameters  c gamma  epsilon into weka? fatih  never miss  thing. make yahoo your homepage.  next part  an html attachment was scrubbed... url https//list.scms.waikato.ac.nz/pipermail/wekalist/attachments/20080208/a6e646c1/attachment0001.html  from grelj.zktpquktddhelsinki.fi sun feb 24 102737 2008 message 3 date fri 8 feb 2008 145843 0200 from harri m.t. saarikoski subject re wekalist multilayerperceptron results to weka machine learning workbench list. messageid 1202475523.47ac5203bf83dwebmail.helsinki.fi contenttype text/plain charsetusascii  but every once   while i find  combination  parameters where   classification doesnt work at all  one sometimes even two classes  seems  be left out   process   confusion matrix looks like   following    b c  classified as  0 6838 4    inf0.25  0 6728 72  b  0.250.75  0 2141 4952  c  0.75inf    what can be  reason  such behaviour? hi. most likely this is  case  overfitting overtraining http//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/overfitting especially  cases where learning was performed too long  where training examples are rare  learner may adjust  very specific random features   training data that have no causal relation   target function. overfitting  backpropagation neural networks like mlp resulting  prediction bias toward one/some   target classes can be caused by  following if misclassified training instances continue  be misclassified iteration after iteration they get overweighted  actually take weight from  correctly classified instances i.e.  weights become imbalanced. furthermore if misclassified instances happen  be clearly concentrated  some classes this can result  confusion matrix that you quoted zero correct instances  some classes.  i have not found  pattern   parameters that causes this. mlp describes  parameters as follows learningrate  the amount  weights are updated. momentum  momentum applied   weights during updating. decay  this will cause  learning rate  decrease. this will divide  starting learning rate by  epoch number  determine what  current learning rate should be. this may help  stop  network from diverging from  target output as well as improve general performance. as far as i know no offshelf formula exists  optimizing these parameters. it is  interchange  parameters   dataset. if you are looking   pattern  performance consider that  parameters operate together learning rate  momentum / decay so that  first two operate  controlling speed  change   latter  stopping  change. ultimately  cost function will depend   task we wish  perform. wiki. if you are getting as high as  85 accuracies from most configurations this suggests that optimal training model  this dataset is produced when  parameters are set  fast burn few iterations so i would say higher learning rate  momentum  fast decay work best do they?. harri   david     yst. terv  best wishes harri saarikoski

subject: re: [python-dev] os.rename on windows
emailtext: raghuram devarakonda wrote  hi   i have submitted  patch http//www.python.org/sf/1704547 that  allows os.rename  replace  destination file if it exists   windows. as part  discussion   tracker martin suggested that  pythondev should discuss  change. does movefilereplaceexisting mean  rename over  existing file is actually atomic? i cannot find any msdn docs that say so  ive seen some that suggest  me that it probably isnt. if its not atomic then this doesnt offer any advantage over shutil.move that i can see   fact would damage  usefulness  os.rename which is currently atomic  all platforms afaik even though it cannot succeed all  time. if movefilereplaceexisting miraculously turns out  be atomic then my opinion is  this feature would be very useful  i would like  crossplatform way  do this  python.  this feature should not be called os.rename which  years has done something else  some platforms  so changing it will invite unnecessary breakage. a new function would be better  perhaps  optional flag. i propose os.atomicrename. also i assume this cannot replace files that are  use?  currently os.rename  windows uses  api movefile which fails  if  destination file exists. the patch replaces this api with  movefileex  uses  flag movefilereplaceexisting which causes   destination file  be replaced if it exists. however this change  is subtle  if there is any existing code that depends  current  os.rename behaviour  windows their code is silently broken with  any destination file being overwritten. but  functionality   replacing is important  i would like  know  best  way   supporting it. if it is deemed that this change is not good  go   asis how about having  optional parameter  os.rename say  winreplace that can be used by callers  explicitly request  replacing? id be ok with  flag  it should have  crossplatform name. requireatomic  replace  something like that. i think  new function makes more sense though.  i must also point out that  patch uses another flag  movefilecopyallowed effectively allowing renamed files  be   separate file systems. the renaming  this case is not atomic  i  used this flag only  support current functionality. it is not  bad  idea  disallow such renames which brings it  line with   behaviour  many unix flavors. this also has  potential  break  code  not silently. i dont quite follow what youre saying here  id be against  operation called rename that sometimes was atomic  sometimes wasnt.  lastly i found  old discussion about  same topic by this list.   http//mail.python.org/pipermail/pythondev/2001may/014957.html   even though guido indicated that he doesnt support api change  this  thread i am posting again as i did not see any one mention  movefileex  that thread. does movefileex solve  atomicity problem that guido raised  that thread? i dont think it does so i think  situation is still  same. andrew.  pythondev mailing list zvlllneumpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pythondev unsubscribe http//mail.python.org/mailman/options/pythondev/pythondev40tangomu.com

subject: re: [opensuse] opensuse 11
emailtext: tero pesonen wrote  on friday 08 february 2008 sloan wrote  tero pesonen wrote  on friday 08 february 2008 randall r schulz wrote  linux is safe when used intelligently.  intelligent use includes using secure passwords   applying security upgrades when theyre made available.  intelligent use excludes running binaries  scripts supplied  by unknown individuals.    if thats too complicated  someone they shouldnt be using   computer at all.  so are windows xp  vista not safe then when used intelligently?  imho using  microsoft operating system intelligently is there   oxymoron here? involves  number  additional restrictions   caveats as well as extra costs as compared  using linux  intelligently which is otoh fairly straightforward.   joe   i dont think running windows xp   desktop securely is rocket  science. my parents have pulled off such  feat  theyve never had  any security issues    people i know they are  least  computer literate. my brother is now  os x  not because   security issues. he just wanted  better computer with  better os than  what his xppowered wintel box was. your parents are lucky. in iraq we had xp machines   department  defence secure network which was completely cut off from  rest   internet  they still caught viruses.   maybe securing  desktop linux system is easier. however as long as it  is not difficult as such   other side security is not  selling  point. ive talked about security  linux  windows users. what they  say is i do not need better  more security since security is   nonissue  begin with. if   other hand openoffice  ms office  became magically easier  use once run  linux then they might  become interested.   money? well some one who buys  branded pc typically already pays   security apps etc. which bring added costs. putting linux  that  hardware at home wont make  money they already paid   windows  os  norton etc. stuff  be returned. windows machines are now so  cheap that money seems no longer  be  motivator that would work   favour  linux at home. even computer magazines no longer write  about linux being free. it seems irrelevant. they write about linux as   equal choice   desktop  not as something that is geeky  yet free. as they used . we need  break  back   mandatory bundling  windows. personally i think computers sold retail should be have lineitem costs with windows as  separate cost from  hardware. its just like payroll taxes deducted out   paycheck  what people dont have  explicitly fork over extra money  they soon forget if they were ever aware  it   first place.

subject: re: [python-dev] os.rename on windows
emailtext: on 4/30/07 andrew bennetts wrote  does movefilereplaceexisting mean  rename over  existing file is actually  atomic? i cannot find any msdn docs that say so  ive seen some that  suggest  me that it probably isnt. even though msdn docs do not say it explicitly i found some discussions claiming that movefilereplaceexisting is atomic. however after seeing your comment i did  more thorough search  i too found some references claiming otherwise. as  last resort i checked cygwin documentation which claims that its rename is posix.1 compliant. if i am not mistaken posix.1 does require atomicity so i am curious how rename is implemented there. i checked out  sources  i will try  find more about their implementation. i completely agree that without positive proof  atomicity there is no point  making this code change.  also i assume this cannot replace files that are  use? a simple test shows that it can indeed replace files that are open. thanks raghu  pythondev mailing list zvlllneumpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pythondev unsubscribe http//mail.python.org/mailman/options/pythondev/pythondev40tangomu.com

subject: re: [python-dev] os.rename on windows
emailtext: raghuram devarakonda wrote  as  last resort i  checked cygwin documentation which claims that its rename is  posix.1 compliant. if i am not mistaken posix.1 does require  atomicity so i am curious how rename is implemented there. the cygwin implementation  rename goes like this 1 try  use movefile 2 try  use movefileex... movefilereplaceexisting 3 try  unlink destination then try  use movefile and as you say cygwin claims it meets posix.1. and posix.1 says if newpath already exists it will be atomically replaced subject   few conditions see errors below so that there is no point at which another process attempting  access newpath will find it missing. clearly unliking  then calling movefile is not atomic. so cygwin is not being honest here because  these less frequent cases  rename will not be atomic. also note mvcrt only tries step 1  cygwins version. which i believe also suggests that its  only version that is atomic. scott  scott dial hmigvscottdial.com scodialcs.indiana.edu  pythondev mailing list zvlllneumpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pythondev unsubscribe http//mail.python.org/mailman/options/pythondev/pythondev40tangomu.com

subject: re: [python-dev] os.rename on windows
emailtext: on 5/1/07 scott dial wrote  the cygwin implementation  rename goes like this   1 try  use movefile  2 try  use movefileex... movefilereplaceexisting  3 try  unlink destination then try  use movefile   and as you say cygwin claims it meets posix.1. and posix.1 says if  newpath already exists it will be atomically replaced subject    few conditions see errors below so that there is no point at which  another process attempting  access newpath will find it missing.  clearly unliking  then calling movefile is not atomic. so cygwin is  not being honest here because  these less frequent cases  rename  will not be atomic. you are right. i just checked cygwins rename code  it is convincing enough  me  withdraw  patch. thanks  all  comments. raghu  pythondev mailing list zvlllneumpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pythondev unsubscribe http//mail.python.org/mailman/options/pythondev/pythondev40tangomu.com

subject: bcc mail storms
emailtext: hi im wondering what advice anyone has regarding this issue when one  our users sends  email with  large amount  local users listed   bcc that contains  sizable attachment it can sometimes trigger  bcc storm. we have  single f5 load balancer that various services flow through. a single email transaction can loop through one piece  equipment multiple times. when one  these bcc storms takes place because  this looping it can max out  interfaces   f5. weve taken some measures  prevent this by reducing  number  different types  services that pass through our load balancer  reverted  using rr dns instead. but im wondering what else can be done. taking  look at  qshape postfix readme i see discussion regarding  defaultdestinationconcurrencylimit parameter which sounds promising  it affects all destinations. it there any way  control concurrency limits   perhost basis?

subject: [spambayes-dev] i used spambayes for class project - thanks!
emailtext: hi spambayes developers i just wanted  let you know that i used spambayes  my term project  my machine learning class   say thanks. i thought there might be some academic interest here  that id share with  list  return   great code  yours that i used. the overall assignment was  do something with evolutionary algorithms. the goal  my project was more  less  attack  spam filter  attempt  use  ea  find weaknesses it might have. i set up  blind watchmaker sort  natural selection/ evolution environment using  spambayes filter that i had trained   old training corpus as  fitness function. the program i wrote attempted  evolve  generic formula that worked sort  like madlibs  write spam emails that could get past  filter. i started off with almost zero knowledge  how  spam filter works  tried  keep it that way while i wrote  algorithm so that it would be as naive as possible. ive since read up  spambayes  some   math behind it  it looks really interesting. im looking forward  taking more time  look through  codebase. now that  project is completed i see where i could have trained  filter  different content  parts   evolution structure that i could have written differently  make this project more successful  thats research  you this was  very quick proof  concept project  if i were  continue with this research there are certainly  lot  things i would do differently  many more complicated techniques that id like  try. if anyone is interested  reading about  project  more detail ive posted  paper i wrote here http//www.cs.brandeis.edu/egifford/classes/egiffordtermproject.pdf thanks again  maintaining this cool project. i hope youll take my contribution   intellectual sense that is intended  not as  attack.  liz gifford  spambayesdev mailing list bsfegmjrrhnqpython.org http//mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/spambayesdev

subject: re: sa-learn weirdness...
emailtext: on fri 8 feb 2008 paolo cravero wrote  dont forget that salearn remembers which messages have been learned.  once your old messages have all been learned you need  feed  it  only new arrivals that is since  last salearn run. no need  keep  180 days worth  ham  spam   temp folder agreed. i rotate learning mailboxes  historical names monthly. in other words everybody has spamassassinspam  spamassassinham mail folders that salearn processes nightly then   first   month those get moved  somthing like spamassassinxyyyymm. in addition  script that launches salearn only tells it about learning folders that have been modified   last three days.  john hardin ka7ohz http//www.impsec.org/jhardin/ ewhxebqimpsec.org falaholic 11174 pgpk  ewhxebqimpsec.org key 0xb8732e79  2d8c 34f4 6411 f507 136c af76 d822 e6e6 b873 2e79  homeland security specializing  tactical bandaids  strategic problems.  eric k.  bruce schneiers blog  4 days until abraham lincolns  charles darwins 199th birthdays

subject: re: bcc mail storms
emailtext: thomas ledbetter  but im wondering what else can be done. taking  look at  qshape  postfix readme i see discussion regarding   defaultdestinationconcurrencylimit parameter which sounds  promising  it affects all destinations.   it there any way  control concurrency limits   perhost basis? indirectly. use  transportmaps entry  deliver mail through  nondefault mail delivery transport  master.cf then set  transport namedestinationconcurrencylimit  that. just clone  smtp ... smtp line  give it  different name   first field then postfix reload. the current qshapereadme file has examples. http//www.postfix.org/qshapereadme.html wietse

subject: re: mail sending problem
emailtext: on fri feb 08 2008 at 040404pm 0530 goutam baul wrote  i have implemented sasl authetication. trend micro net suit is being used as   anti spam/anti virus software. since last few days i am finding that  some   users out  total 900 users 3 has reported  issue so far  are not able  send mail  any address outside  my domain. the log entry  that i am getting is something like   feb 8 155429 mail postfix/smtpd9334 noqueue reject rcpt from  unknown59.183.54.228 554  recipient address  rejected access denied from   protosmtp helo did this user actually authenticate? all indications are that he  she did not. just because  server allows authentication does not mean that all users correctly configure their mail clients  use it.  viktor. disclaimer offlist followups get list replies  get ignored. please do not ignore  replyto header. to unsubscribe from  postfixusers list visit http//www.postfix.org/lists.html  click  link below if my response solves your problem  best way  thank me is  not send  it worked thanks followup. if you must respond please put it worked thanks   subject so i can delete these quickly.

subject: mail attachements truncated
emailtext: hi ive got following problem. sometimes mail attachments are truncated   email is send  files are corrupted. mail header contains then xamavisalert bad header mime error error part did not end with expected boundary. and that is true  there is no boundary  mime  data stream is not completed. ive turned  detailed postfix debugging  it looks like at some point there is smtpget eof instead   someip quit  someip 221 2.0.0 bye attachment is truncated after different sizes sometimes 65kb sometimes 200kb  after different times 25s 100s. the only common thing ive found is that all such mails come from one internet provider that is publicgprs.centertel.pl i guess it might be  problem with this provider orange poland    other hand they can send emails through other mail servers without such  problem. i got stuck with it. is there any way  debug it more? do you have any ideas what could be  cause? i use postfix 2.3.8  debian stable  amavis etc. thanks  advance jakub

subject: re: mail attachements truncated
emailtext: jakub nadolny  ive got following problem. sometimes mail attachments are truncated    email is send  files are corrupted.   mail header contains then  xamavisalert bad header mime error error part did not end with  expected boundary. and that is true  there is no boundary  mime   data stream is not completed. are you using  beforequeue smtpdproxy content filter?  ive turned  detailed postfix debugging  it looks like at some  point there is  smtpget eof  instead    someip quit   someip 221 2.0.0 bye in that case postfix aborts  mail transaction  will not deliver  mail. however it is possible that beforequeue smtpdproxy content filter does not properly handle  aborted transaction  delivers  mail anyway. in that case send  bug report   content filter maintainer. wietse

emailtext: call  papers subtrack  realtime systems  date 05 http//www.idt.mdh.se/date05rt/cfp the 8th date conference  exhibition is  main european event bringing together design automation researchers users  vendors as well as specialists   design test  manufacturing  electronic systems  circuits. date is also europes leading commercial exhibition showing  stateart  design  test tools methodologies ip  design services. both  conference   exhibition together with  many user group meetings fringe meetings university booth  social events offer  wide variety  opportunities  meet  exchange information. subtrack on realtime systems  this year date features  subtrack  realtime systems  provide  forum  bring together embedded  realtime systems researchers  practitioners. submissions  papers describing original research  all areas  realtime computing  communication systems including design analysis implementation testing  tools are invited  consideration towards presentation  publication. chair gerhard fohler malardalen university sweden co chair sanjoy baruah university  north carolina usa technical program committee alan burns university  york uk giorgio buttazzo university  pavia italy jeandominique decotignie csem switzerland peter puschner vienna university  technology austria tei wei kuo national taiwan university taiwan roc important dates submission deadline sep 12 2004 firm notification  acceptance nov 12 2004 cameraready papers due dec 04 2004 submission instructions please visit  date 05 site at http//www.dateconference.com  further information about  conference.

computing  mathematics pierre deligne phillip griffiths  david mumford are sharing  2008 wolf foundation prize  mathematics. deligne was honored  his work  mixed hodge theory  weil conjectures  riemannhilbert correspondence   his contributions  arithmetic griffiths  his work  variations  hodge structures  theory  periods  abelian integrals   his contributions  complex differential geometry  mumford  his work  algebraic surfaces  geometric invariant theory   laying  foundations   modern algebraic theory  moduli  curves  theta functions. the three share  100000 award. this years crafoord subject: ietf-dkim digest vol 106 issue 5
emailtext: send ietfdkim mailing list submissions  gfkyhddlmipassoc.org to subscribe  unsubscribe via  world wide web visit http//mipassoc.org/mailman/listinfo/ietfdkim  via email send  message with subject  body help  qvcimnfiqkwxudxmipassoc.org you can reach  person managing  list at qghtrnrqbhlpvmipassoc.org when replying please edit your subject line so it is more specific than re contents  ietfdkim digest... todays topics 1. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 eric allman 2. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 hector santos 3. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt discardable/exclusive douglas otis 4. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 j d falk 5. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 eric allman 6. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt discardable/exclusive eric allman 7. re draftietfdkimssp02.txt discardable/exclusive steve atkins  from jbtlfzfgsendmail.org sun feb 24 102737 2008 message 1 date thu 07 feb 2008 165438 0800 from eric allman subject re ietfdkim draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 to hector santos cc dkim list messageid 02da2d6eb1065d7c54044f2crieux.neophilic.com contenttype text/plain charsetusascii formatflowed hector some  what you say is correct  other descriptions  changes  ssp02 dont match what we were trying  do. it may well be that we didnt get  wording right yet. first  confession most   major changes  02 are my doing. in particular i think i pushed some things onto jim that went further than he had wanted. i think its unfair  ask jim  defend things that are basically my own responsibility. i particularly apologize because i went   major surgery just about  time this was hitting  fan  im not yet fully functioning. theres  certain philosophical difference between folks  this list. some want ssp  be extremely specific. others have gone  at length that  ssp spec has no right  authority  impose its own will  receivers. i have sympathies  both positions  i have  agree that there is no chance that we can successfully dictate how receivers operate. ive said publicly many times that receivers will simply ignore  specs if it makes their lives better  as we see today with intentional violations  rfc 2822. ssp02 is  attempt  pare ssp down  appeal   second set. yes that weakens ssp  that seems inevitable at this point. in particular im concerned that without giving receivers any guidance  how certain situations should be handled well end up   fairly chaotic state. however i do agree that such guidance should probably go   nonstandardstrack document. a few specific points from your message on february 6 2008 14658 am 0500 hector santos wrote ...  with ssp02/asp we lost  powerful ssp01 dkimall protection  against 3rd party fraud. speaking about ssp02 im not sure how you see weve lost that protection. in 01 dkimall specifically allowed 3ps thirdparty signatures so arguably it was weaker before. under ssp02  receiver could decide that 3ps should be treated more harshly where more harshly doesnt necessarily mean discard  it could just mean do content scanning   message. we did remove all discussion  3ps. the extended list discussion around them made it clear that we just dont have enough operational knowledge at this time  understand how they should work. as such we are now leaving all interpretation  3rd party signatures up   receiver. that doesnt mean weve necessarily lost  ability  handle 3ps   distinct way  it will have  go into another document at least  now.  the never concept can still be covered using dkimdiscardable    null dkim public key.   the exclusive concept can still be covered using dkimdiscardable. except that discardable doesnt prohibit 3ps. it doesnt even say that messages without any signatures must  even should be discarded. all it says is how  purported author domain views  messages that it sends out. the furthest it goes is  say that  purported author domain encourages  recipients  discard it.  but anything related  3rd party signers was completely eliminated   ssp02/asp. even though ssp02 dkimall is  always sign   1st party authors concept it is basically  dkimdiscardable  without semantics  rejection. dkimdiscardable failures is  explicit with  rejection control. dkimall failures are not. ssp02 dkimall is not  always sign  1st party authors concept. it doesnt even mention first parties any more than it mentions 3rd parties. all it says is when  message left my control i had signed it. it says absolutely nothing about how  receiver should handle  message. similarly  as noted above dkimdiscardable makes no normative assertions about what  receiver should do with  message. it is impossible  say anything about when  receiver should reject messages without stepping into  forbidden territory  forcing  certain behavior   receiver.  in short dkimall is  spf version  softfail where you can  record it  you do not take any rejection action  it. just  like spf. theres nothing that prevents  recipient from rejecting messages under  dkimall condition. in fact if we did it as intended there is no normative language anywhere  ssp02 about how  receiver should process messages be they signed unsigned  3ps. ...  but that is not  case with dkim. here we have 100 detectable  fraud capabilities that is unrelated  legitimate multiple hope ip  issues  asp is mandating  flawed inherent policy that receivers  should ignore certain kinds  obvious fraudulent messages. im not speaking  asp  ssp02 makes  is intended  make no normative restrictions  when  receiver should accept  reject any messages. another addition  ssp02 was  concept   evaluator. this was added purely  try  make it clear that ssp is merely one input into  decision process. the evaluator decides whether  reject  message quarantine it do additional content scanning  it accept it without further scanning redirect it   fbi post it  usenet  anything else it cares  do. my hope was that creating  explicit entity that makes  decision  clearly declare it out  scope we would clarify  limits  ssp. it is my sincere hope that we will quickly gain enough experience that new documents can be produced providing further guidance not requirements  how  evaluator should interpret ssp  broadest interoperability. eric  from mwbfbflsantronics.com sun feb 24 102737 2008 message 2 date fri 08 feb 2008 062805 0500 from hector santos subject re ietfdkim draftietfdkimssp02.txt asp/ssp section 2.8 to eric allman cc dkim list messageid 47ac3cc5.3000407santronics.com contenttype text/plain charsetiso88591 formatflowed eric i sincerely appreciate your response  i do hope you are  your way  full recovery from your surgery. i had  hip replacement  few years back  it was  first time   long time i was forced into  prolonged vacation from work.  it been  long road  where we are now. a road where we tuned nearly every stone  discussed  even worked out. there were some remaining issues  ones that i dont believe were not addressable. the best i can describe  concerns is that we lost  potential  protocol consistency fraud. for example you pointed out ssp01 dkimall offered 3rd party signatures  this could be deemed weaker i agree with that point. however i never indicated that  valid 3rd party was ever classified as secured   lack  one is were  power   concept is found. the concept is really subject: re: a few multiple dispatch questions
emailtext: on tue aug 05 2008 at 061730pm 0200 jonathan worthington wrote  hi   i am currently reviewing bits   spec surrounding multiple dispatch    course have  question  two ill probably have some more  later as  dust settles  my head.   1 the spec says     a proto also adds  implicit multi  all routines    same short name within its scope unless they have  explicit modifier.     if you write   proto sub foothing  ...   sub fooint x  ...   only sub foo  ...    does this give some kind  error because youve declared something  with only  it clearly cant be  only one because we also have   proto  there? id consider it  error.  2 if i write   multi sub fooint blah  ...   1  proto sub fooblah is thingy  ...   2  multi sub foo  ...   3   does 1 get  thingy trait  not because it was declared before   proto was? im clear that 3 gets it... i think  proto cannot be expected  work retroactively. in fact i think its probably  error  declare  proto after  nonproto   same scope.  3 the spec says     a parameter list may have at most one double semicolon parameters after  it are  never considered  multiple dispatch except  course that they can  still  veto if their number  types mismatch.     does  veto take place once  multiple dispatch has given us   candidate  we try  bind  parameters   signature  as part    multiple dispatch? for example supposing i declare   multi fooint  num b  ...   1  multi fooint  str b  ...   2  multi fooint  num b num c  ...   3   what happens with these?   foo2 randomthing.new  ambiguous dispatch error  foo2 2.5  ambiguous dispatch error  1 because 2 vetos?  foo1 2.5 3.4  ambiguous dispatch error  3 because only one with  arity match?   basically what im getting at is are all  these multimethods  ambiguous because they all have  same long name  just because  binding fails doesnt make us return into  multiple dispatch  algorithm? this is what im kinda expecting  would mean every one   these fails. but i just want  check that is what was meant by   wording. i believe veto is giving  wrong idea here as something that happens after  fact. whats  term  only allowing acceptable candidates  put their names   ballot? anyway as tsa surmises  ballot is vetted  stacked  advanceonly those candidates that could bind are considered  be part   candidate set. in  abstract candidates that cannot match never get their names   ballot though  course  implementation might choose  determine this lazily as long as it preserves  same semantics. alternately even if  list  valid candidates is determined eagerly if  candidate list construction is memoized based   typeshape   capture it will generally not have  be redone until you see  different typeshape where  meaning  different may depend  how specific  signatures are   particular  whether any   signatures rely  subset constraints including individual values which are just degenerate subsets. larry

emailtext: we are still   process  finalizing  trec 2007 spam track guidelines. this is  interim report. we should have  final guidelines by  end  june. in  meantime please feel free  post queries  comments  this list. the primary tasks will use  same tool kit  data format as last year i.e.  trec spam filter evaluation toolkit available here http//plg.uwaterloo.ca/gvcormac/spam/ the active learning task will use  different version   toolkit  be available shortly. the three tasks are online filtering with immediate feedback.  exactly  same task as  trec 2005  2006 online filtering with delayed/incomplete/noisy feedback.  same tools as   trec 2006 delayted feedback   test data may not contain train commands  every message  some   train commands may be wrong so as  simulate user underreporting  user error. emphasis will be placed  correct classification   large number  messages with no feedback. for example there may be no feedback   last half   messages online active filtering with active learning.  different tools  task from trec 2006 active learning filters will perform line classification as   other two tasks  will be allowed  query  true class ham  spam   fraction   messages chosen by  filter. this will be effected by  additional command query added   toolkit query where is  message previously classified by  filter. filters will be submitted  nist date  be determined  probably midjuly after which  public corpus will be released. results   public corpus will also be submitted  nist probably late august.  gordon v. cormack cs dept university  waterloo canada n2l 3g1 qcdjhryliuwaterloo.ca http//cormack.uwaterloo.ca/cormack

if so you should be writing software at airwave wireless. our team practices extreme programming xp so we spend most  our time writing code. we believe that running code  short feedback loops speak louder than excessive documentation  monthlong design meetings. we practice testdriven development  have  comprehensive suite  tests... over 31000 at last count. we pair program so youll learn  system quickly  have  great time doing it. we have short release cycles which means your talents wont sit idle working  projects that never see  light  day. software you write today will be managing enterprise networks  just  couple  weeks. weve been cited as  longest running continuous xp project   industry six years  counting so we have gotten quite good at embracing xps advantages while avoiding its pitfalls. personally i enjoy working at airwave more than any job ive ever had. i am excited  come into work every day i work hard  eight hours solving challenging problems  then go home  lead  well balanced life outside  work. when im at work i get  interact closely with  group that is brilliant funny motivated  inspiring. i spend most   day smiling laughing  learning. the team weve built is truly  special group  im proud  honored  be  part  it. excited? good now   nuts  bolts. airwave developers write software  several different languages primarily objectoriented perl  linux systems. we use apache modperl2  our front end ui  postgresql  our backend persistence layer. since we manage network devices knowledge  network protocols would be  plus e.g. snmp tftp  http. rolling out  wireless network is  daunting task  our products help  ease that burden. we build network management software that is used by many   leading it organizations at fortune 500 companies major universities hospitals  other prominent institutions. our industryleading software helps plan configure manage  monitor some   largest wireless networks   planet. required skills  perl  objectoriented programming  strong refactoring  design ability desired skills  experience developing automated tests  apache modperl  basic sql postgresql experience  plus  experience with agile software development  function  logical programming expeience  linux application development  knowledge  tcp/ip  802.11 wireless networking contact information at http//jobs.perl.org/job/7902contact

emailtext: alxfrag wrote  hi   i have  couple  questions regarding sasl.   in main.cf i have     smtpdsasllocaldomain  smtpdsaslpathsmtpd   brokensaslauthclientsyes   smtpdrecipientrestrictionspermitmynetworkspermitsaslauthenticatedrejectunauthdestination    smtpdsenderrestrictionschecksenderaccess  hash/etc/postfix/blocksendershash/etc/postfix/mydomains   smtpdsenderloginmapsldap/etc/postfix/localrecipients.cf   smtpdsenderrestrictionsrejectauthenticatedsenderloginmismatch   smtpdrestrictionclassesverifylogin   verifyloginrejectsenderloginmismatch       mydomains   mydomain1 verifylogin  mydomain2 verifylogin      using this configuration user1mydomain1 cannot pretend he is   different user. for example he cannot send  email saying he is  user2mydomain2.   question1 how can i exclude  user from this rule based  his ip?   main.cf ive added mynetworks127.0.0.1 hisipaddress  it does  not work. add permitmynetworks at  top  smtpdsenderrestrictions.   question2 the rule above works fine  all users when they use   webmail client  any other client. the only problem is with users who  use squirrelmail. they still can send emails with  fake from  address postfix cannot stop them.  smtpd restrictions only apply  mail sent via smtp. if squirrelmail uses  sendmail command then that wont work.  since squirrelmail always exectutes as  same user your webserver uid theres not much  do except finding  way  squirrelmail  implement  restriction.  any ideas?   thanks  advance   alex

emailtext: on fri feb 08 2008 at 020245pm 0100 paolo cravero wrote  arthur dent wrote   hmmm... not delete exactly   salearn job take so long that   archivemail job has kicked off  finds  tempspam  tempham mboxes    mail directory  dutifully chops out anything older than 180 days. i  didnt think that that would be  problem  maybe its upsetting salearn?  i will try switch  order   jobs archivemail running first  see if  that makes  difference..   at this point you have probably already swapped  two processes.   i think salearn   process feeding it does not like  chopping. yes. sorry i didnt post  update because i was embarrassed at my own stupidity  not thinking it through more carefully before posting my original message. switching  jobs round did indeed mean that salearn is no longer getting interfered with by archivemail while its  midlearn. it now behaves quite sensibly.  well as i explained  my previous post  tempham folder is   concatenation  all my nonspam folders. mail that is older than 180 days is  taken off at one end  new mail c. 3040 per day added  at  other.  the total remains roughly constant.   dont forget that salearn remembers which messages have been learned. once  your old messages have all been learned you need  feed  it only new  arrivals that is since  last salearn run. no need  keep 180 days  worth  ham  spam   temp folder yes i understand that. its not that i keep  temp folder  spam/ham i dont. i know that it only needs  learn  new mails. its just that im basically lazy  it seemed far easier  me simply  take all my nonspam folders  copy them together into one big temporary file run salearn  it  then delete  temporary file eg /bin/bash cat /mail/mailinglists/ /mail/workstuff/ /mail/admin/  tempham salearn ham mbox /mail/tempham rm /mail/tempham im no bashscripting wiz that much should be obvious so i could think  no easy way  strip only todays mails out  my 20odd folders  just feed those  salearn. my way i need  do nothing myself  job takes about half  hour  im asleep when it happens... ok salearn has  work  bit harder than it needs   hey better it than me the 180 days thing is because i choose  keep only  last 6 months approx mail  each  my 20  so folders  rest being zipped into  gzip archive using archivemail  very neat little utility btw  180 days is its default setting see i told you i was lazy.  let salearn complete  then chop  folder. just concatenate   process rather than schedule it  crontab. it should fix your apparent  weirdness.   paolo thanks  all  help  suggestions. much appreciated... mark
